	abstract = {This article presents a research which examines the psychographic characteristics of members and non-members of the radio and television audiences. A commercial research firm obtained data for this research by personal interview in a large city in the southwestern U.S. They interviewed 754 randomly selected respondents and obtained information on demographic and psychographic characteristics of the respondents as well as on respondents exposure to radio and {TV}. The distribution of the demographic characteristics of the sample indicated that the data were representative of metropolitan populations in the southwestern U.S. Researchers derived two categories of radio and {TV} usage from the data with users identified as those respondents who were exposed to the respective medium for a minimum period of 15 minutes during the week prior to the survey. The psychographic characterization of the respondents began with a factor analysis of responses on the 29 activities, interests, and opinions ({AIO}) statements included in the survey. Principal axis factor analysis followed by a variance rotation produced five factors that explained 87 percent of the variance in respondents measured {AIO}.},
